<rating>5< /rating>< Text>
A great little.dive bar with amazing Thai food. The bartender and chef was our gracious host. We got the Shrimp Wraps, Mama Noodle Soup, and Pad Kee Mow (drunken noodles). All of it was great. Shrimp Wraps were perfectly crispy. The soup was flavorful. The Pad Kee Mow was so delicious and spicy. Also tried a Thai lager and some Thai tea.

We will return. Mainly suggestion is not to bring a big group just because the staff is small, intimate, and friendly, so small groups may be best.</Text>

Incredible food, drinks, and service with a laid-back atmosphere in a family-run establishment, what‚Äôs not to love? We had the Chicken Kra Pow, Bat Wings, and Pork Jerky, all of which my companion, who has spent a great deal of time in Thailand swears is better than anything he‚Äôs had in Bangkok!

The atmosphere on a post-pandemic Monday night was enjoyably chill and laid back, but we were told that if you‚Äôre looking for a great party vibe to come in on the weekends. Either way, I can‚Äôt recommend this place enough!</Review>

<userid>106650107911059379329</userid><Name>Anand Pandya< /Name><Rate>5<//Rate><time>1555168934346< /time><Text>A great Thai restaurant in a friendly dive bar, Thai Angel did not look like a promising place to have dinner. It is relatively dark and looks more oriented towards drinking than eating. However, I soon discovered that the drink menu has several tasty original cocktails and that they have their own free parking lot behind the building. The bat wing appetizer was great with a dipping sauce that had a surprisingly complex flavor. Our entrees were also great. < Review>
If it were possible to make a zero star review I would. Before I came to Sheila Bella I had perfectly fine eyebrows. I just wanted them to be a little darker and more defined. I saw their posts on Instagram, I saw the videos and when I saw the 399 special I said why not. On the day of my appointment I was scared, and so nervous because I was about to get a freaking tattoo on my face. The tech Leslie hardly talked to me and reassured me throughout the process. The only time she spoke with me was when I needed to approve the shape and color. I showed her exactly how I wanted the stokes to look like and how I wanted them shaped. Yes I approved the shape and yes I approved the color. What I did not approve of was the thickness of the stokes. Since they were taping me for the special of course I acted like I was ok with the brows. As soon as I got into my car I started crying. The hair strokes were so aggressively thick. I was embarrassed to even lift my head up as I walked to my car. I had to spend two and a half weeks hiding from everyone because I didn't want them to notice these chola like sharpie eyebrows. The only thing consoling me was thinking they will fade...they will thin out. NOPE. They did not thin out. What I have on my face are not even realistic hair strokes but LINES. I know the manager or whoever will reply to this with "I must get the touch up to make them look better, It's a process" Why the hell would I go back and PAY 200 for a touch up and go through that embarrassment on my face for two and a half weeks again. Even if I did decided to go back and get it done with Sheila herself, I would have to pay ANOTHER 100 bucks just to switch techs. I was not satisfied at all with how they came out in the first place. Not only did my eyebrows have A LOT of scabbing, but when the scabs did come off, it ripped off my real hair with them. What I am left with are these aggressive lines on my face which I will have to pay to get taken off now. Please, please, please do your research when it comes to microblading.</Review>

< Review>
Four of us (two couples) participated in a private tasting September 2019 were really impressed not only with the quality wines that were poured, but also the AWESOME tasting room environment! The '59 vette, vintage bikes, and Rolling Stones pinball all add to the most immersive tasting experience that we had that entire week in the Napa Valley.  Yes, we were very happy to ship several cases of Superb James Cole Wine (The Suede is HUGE) back home and continue to place orders as value options are presented.  A "must-do" experience when you visit Napa!</Review>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
Excellent experience at this beautiful winery. Staff greeted us upon entry, and escorted us to a personal session. Upon there, they do give you a list of wines for the tasting. In addition the staff will fully explain the wines, but then takes it further and understand the science behind male and female taste buds. This was particularly interesting because my wife and I do enjoy different styles of wines.

The location is set off of the road ‚Äúa hidden gem‚Äù in plain site with a beautiful scenery.  Also, their symbol and the meaning behind it lives up to the how well the winery functions.

I‚Äôm happy we found this place. Well, my first time and my wife second time after her ‚Äúladies‚Äù trip with the family.

You will enjoy it there.<//review>

<Review>When I think about what makes a winery a great winery, I think about: 1. quality of the wine, 2. overall experience, 3. wine club member experience, and 4. interest in returning.

1. The wine is fantastic. My wife and I primarily drink cabernet and cabernet blends, and the reds really stand out. they're complex and long lasting (except in my glass).

2. The experience onsite at the winery is memorable. From the architecture to the staff to the view. It's a memory that comes back each time I have a glass of 2016 Cabernet.

3. We joined as club members, and not only have kept up the membership (not always the case everywhere) but often add bottles to the shipment. The whole team is super responsive whenever I have a question.

4. Would we return? Absolutely! And we tell all of our friends about them!

Keep up the work James Cole, and keep those shipments coming!< /Review><user_name>Nate Smith< /user_name><Response>{'time': 1618624032633, 'text': 'Hi Nate, you are truly kind for your words about our wines and property. <Text>My wife and I have been visiting both Napa and Sonoma for the past 30 years. We live in the midwest and rarely find smaller production wines. During our numerous trips we learned to ask different wineries to suggest other wineries we should visit. While in Sonoma at one of the best zinfadel producers, I asked the tasting room host to recommend his favorite Cabernet Sauvignon producer. He stated James Cole Winery won that designation hands down!
We arranged a tasting for the following day. Wow, we were blown away by the phenomenal wines and the friendly tasting room staff. We purchased wines to take with us and regretted we did not join the wine club at that time.
The following summer I celebrated my birthday by bringing my entire nuclear family to Napa/Sonoma for a wine experience. My sons were both very knowledgeable about wines while the majority of the group were novices, we had a total of 17 people. We planned a visit to James Cole on Wednesday. Again we were blown away by a tasting of some of the best Cabs we had ever tasted, blends were great also.With the large group again I hesitated joining the wine club however when we returned on Friday with only a few dedicated wine consumers, I signed up.
I have been a member of many clubs over the years, they come and go. The wines change as does the quality.
For the past 5 years I have been a member of the Coalition Wine Club at James Cole. Not once have I ever been disappointed in any bottle of their wine I have opened. I have my favorites, my wife has hers and when our children visit, they always open a James Cole from the cellar. Keep up the dedication to great wines. You are truly my favorite Napa producer!< /Text><pictures>None<//pictures><response>{'time': 1619283019924, 'text': 'Thank you so much for your support! < Review>
Amazing wines, beautiful setting and the best staff in all of Napa! We've been members of JC for about 10 years and it just keeps getting better and better. James and Colleen are the epitome of the Napa dream. They put their heart and soul into the winery and it shows.  Not only are the wines phenomenal, the tasting experience is too.  Dustin made sure we felt right at home at our last tasting (as always) and made the experience extra special for our first time guests.  We are always excited to share of our love of James Cole with others...but not too many because we love the initmate experience which is vastly different from a large, commercial winery.  If in the area, make sure to put James Cole on your short list.  You will not be disappointed!<//Review>

<userid>107758617389947014398< /userid>< Name>
Dave Jones< /Name>
<Date>1618607234131< /Date><rate>5< /rate>< text>
Of all of the wineries we have visited in the Napa Valley, James Cole holds a special place in our journey as wine enthusiasts.  The best description I can come up with is "winemaking with attitude".  On the lighter side, their roses and chardonnay stand apart from retail labels.  The chardonnay has a hint of butter without overdoing it and the rose is extremely drinkable and refreshing.  Where JC knocks it out of the park is on their reds.  The Marls red blend is tastefully bold for those who aren't into lots of tannins, but remains complex, unlike most red blends.  The cabs, some of which are actually barrel-fermented, possess character right at the point of release and have the foundations to age to be even better when laid down.  My personal favorite is the JC Malbec which I would call a "power rock" red. At a middle price point, it's bold and complex without being overwhelming.  We drink some immediately and lay the rest down.  We discovered this amazing boutique winery on our first visit to the valley and it remains our favorite.  We simply love both the vibe and the wine.< /text>

None<//pictures>

<Review>James Cole is a member of the upper echelon of Napa Valley wineries. It‚Äôs location at the southern end of the Silverado Trail is coveted and the small stone winery and tasting room exude a cool and sophisticated vibe. The grounds are just lovely. You‚Äôll find that the staff are friendly, enthusiastic and well-trained veterans of the industry. If you‚Äôre in search of a varietal not on Cole‚Äôs menu or just need a restaurant recommendation, these are the folks to ask. James Cole‚Äôs wine offerings are broad but not too broad. Enjoy their powerful Napa cab or rich blends, well-textured Chardonnay, delicate Sauvignon Blanc and really interesting Pinot. Oh, and try the newish rose. All a great treat and often at a very competitive price point. Cheers!

Deane Lamont< /Review>< Pictures>

<Text>For some reason I thought this was a larger producer, but the cases produced for all their varietals is in the 100's. They do make a range of wines, interestingly.

My wife and I preferred different wines, she liked the Napa cab, and I preferred their "reserve" cab, from one of the nearby mountains (can't remember which off the top of my head). The Napa cab was a bit more tannic, and had some more chalky earth notes.

The ice wine is pricey, but is such a great dessert wine, and I'm a sucker for dessert wines...

Nice walk-in tasting experience, beautiful facility, friendly people.</Text><Gmap_id>0x808501057cc3d49d:0x6b3cc1e09ad745eb< /Gmap_id></record>

1532584335209< /Time>
<rate>5<//rate>< text>
This has quickly become my favorite bar to hang out at and grab a beer. They serve no liquor here. They also have plenty of local brews available which is awesome. Its a very locals only type place and I love that. You don't have a huge crowd there every weekend being loud and obnoxious. They also have daily drink specials as well as pool tables and a back patio area for smoking. Theres parking in the back and front so thats convenient. Bartenders are always super cool and can always recommend a good beer to try out, they'll give you a sample before pouring a full glass. Needless to say this has become my go to bar even though I live about 10 miles away.<//text>

< rating>
3</rating>
< review>
Mini bar is just that, mini.  This small establishment it a fine place for a drink with great cocktails, jazz playing and some cool art on the walls.  There are some tables up front and a small back room and a arching bar in the middle.  If there are more than about 10 people in the bar it feels kinda crowded.  It is also a challenge to get to the restroom which is precariously places in a tight corner.  Overall though good crowd, good drinks and fun place on Divis.< /review>

<userid>112191390618356281229<//userid><username>Da ph<//username><date>1569200563331<//date>< rating>
5<//rating>
< text>
I'm 35 years old and finally decided to make the call to Lasik Vision Institute after hearing how good lasik has been to people I work with. When I went in for my consult in Huntington Beach, Dr. Nguyen treated me very nicely and provided me with all the options and details I needed to make my informed decision. The only part was my concern on the cost and how I would be paying for it. Diana helped me with the financing. She made it very simple for me and set me up with zero interest via Care Credit. So, I had my lasik surgery on July 19. It was way better than what I thought it was going to be. Dr. Bavand made me feel comfortable and I did not feel a thing ( they provided plenty of numbing medication and sedative). Dr. Bavand let me know what he was doing every step of the way. I felt like I was under his surgical care in less than 10 minutes. I have had two follow up appointments and Rose checks me in and gets me ready to see Dr. Nguyen. Rose and Dr. Nguyen make it a pleasant visit answering all my questions and addressing what post follow up care I need to pay closer attention to. This office is very professional and clean. I remember reading how dry the eyes feel after having this surgery. I experienced super dry eyes the first couple of weeks along with light sensitivity during the day, and glare at night. I would use the drops as instructed, all day, and also would wear the dark eye shades( sunglasses) they provided me throughout the day, even at work on the computer. Now that I am 2 months post surgery, I use the drops 4-6 times a day, and wear my sunglasses when driving. I have no issues with glare at night. The eye drops they recommended are those daily use vials that I bought at Costco. They feel soo good. keep your eyes moist! Lots of Omega-3 people! If you are thinking about Lasik, I say go for it! Better now, than later. You can finance and make a monthly payment. Or put a couple of hundred down, and drop your payment. My surgery was just under $3600 for what my eyes needed. Everyone is different. Your consult should help determine what is right for you. Go online, you can see when they have special discounts. I also have VSP insurance which is who recommended me to these guys. Worth every penny!!!</text>

< name>
Aries franhens<//name>
<rating>5<//rating>< Text>
Disclaimer: I had my surgery Oct. 2017.

I remember everything as it happened yesterday! I wanted to get the Lasik done for such a long time, but looking for the right Dr. To perform the procedure took me a long time to find. I seriously had  so many consultations with Doctors all over southern California but none ever felt right. It wasn't until I had my first consultation with Dr. Melikian and his amazing team! ( Dr. Nguyen , Beverly, Jonas and Rose) that I fell in love with the place and I knew I wanted to have my surgery with them. When I met with the doctor for the first time, I had a list of questions I asked every doctor I would meet, and Dr. Melik was super patient with me and my mom; answer; he every single question and  concern we had, was throughout and above all, he had the best attitude, bedside manners and he was just super super nice. The whole team was and has always been extremely nice and welcoming, which is something that almost never happens at  doctors offices.

The procedure
If you have been doing your research, you will know the procedure itself is very quick ( I recommend watching YouTube videos). On the day of the surgery they ask you to come dress comfortably, which I did, because after the procedure they are going to prescribe you a sedative(if I'm not mistaken) that will help with any pain and will help you sleep it off until the next day).  So you come in in the morning, they are going to make you watch a video of what's going to happen and what to expect after. The team will give you a care packet with eye wear you must wear for some good two weeks post lasik (to not accidentally rub your eyes when you sleep). A fter all the videos and explanations, I was super excited to start and to be honest I was not scared or nervous at all! but they will offer you and recommend you to take a relaxer pill. Which I did but I kinda regret taking because it obviously makes you Druggy and relaxed, but I just hate feeling of dizziness so this is a personal choice.
The procedure seriously lasts like 5 seconds each eye approximately. It's ridiculously short! It made me regret all the years it took me to made up my mind to get the surgery done. I walked in with blurry vision, and 5 minutes later I walked out ...well still with watery blurry vision but it was much better than before xD. I then walked out all happy and excited, took the medication to knock me out for the day and I slept the day away until the next morning.
I did not feel any pain at all, I don't know if that's usual but I had no pain , no headache and my eyes looked great! There was no sign that I had just had lasik done. I could see crystal clear! For the first time since I was 11 years old, I did not have to reach out to grab my glasses first thing when I woke up in the morning. It was so amazing, having HD vision, see signs that were fAr away ! It is seriously a life changing decision. I have no regrets up to this day! My eyes did end up being dry and I do have to use eye drops multiple times a day. If I stay too long without eye drops, I do get pretty bad headache. They say that normally it does away with time, but I just happen to have the bad luck that it has not. The doctor gives you alternatives, like eye plugs, which definitely help SOOOOO much! Look them up, they are very handy. It is really hard to live with dry eyes, but at the same time having great vision is so amazing and for me kinda worth the dryness.
Up to this date, I still visit Dr. Nguyen and Dr.Melik for follow ups to make sure my eyes health is still goodand Make sure my sight is clear and amazing. I am still really happy with the results, even though my eyes are really dry.< /Text>

< Review>
I had been wanting to get lasik and get rid of my glasses for years and on April 16th I finally went for it. I was nervous at first, of course, but the staff is so informative and friendly that everything was so comfortable. I came for a candidacy check up first and scheduled my surgery promptly after. The day of the surgery I was given Valium to relax and numbing eye drops, then waited for the doctor. It literally took 10 seconds of lasering per eye and a good night sleep to change everything. Beverly walked me to my car where my ride was waiting because he thought it was going to take longer. The next day I came to my post-op appointment and I already had 20/20 vision and only minor discomfort due to dryness, which can be easily solved by following the doctors orders and using your drops. < Review>
We were in need of a new bed and rather than buy online, (a place I usually go for many items) we actually wanted to touch and feel and try what was available in the sleep arena.  We could not be more pleased with our experience at Mancini's Sleep World in Dublin and cannot recommend this store highly enough.  Our salesman, John, greeted us politely when we entered and then asked us a few questions in order to save us time and point us toward the beds that would best suite our needs.  The selection was immense and as we were putting down a large amount of money on a bed, we were so happy to have been able to touch, feel, and lie on the beds and experience their features, giving us a bit more security in our decisions.  (An added bonus is the four month "sample" period the store affords, really helping you feel secure in your purchase.) After a great deal of sampling, not for lack of comfort, just simply because we wanted to be sure, we finally chose a bed.  Throughout the process, John was always available to answer our questions, yet he also gave us the alone time to we needed to enjoy the beds so we never felt pressured.  The entire process was so easy and actually enjoyable.  Our new bed will be delivered and set up tomorrow, truly an easy, seamless process with a great guarantee!!  I cannot imagine that I had contemplated purchasing a bed online, after the ease of shopping at Mancini's, I now realize what a mistake that would have been. <userid>114714423203837540287< /userid>< name>
Patricia Brantley<//name>
<Date>1555266748527<//Date><rating>4</rating>< review>
Solano Town Center also known as Solano Mall seems to have improved over the past few years. The selection of stores is okay for a smaller city. The inside is clean and there are ample places to sit and rest. It is a bit dim inside and could use some brighter lighting and I think they rely a bit too much on the skylights. The outskirts of the mall, stores outside the mall proper, has a variety of restaurants, a Trader Joe's, Michael's and a Ross, so if you can't find what you need IN the mall maybe you can  in the surrounding stores. There are EV chargers on the North side of the mall and 2 at Macys. Be careful in the parking lot as it does have its share of shady characters. Otherwise, it's a good place to find what you need.<//review>

<Time>1584365244515</Time><rate>3< /rate><text>Still good stores unlike most malls with a bunch a one off fly-by-night stores that are basically just space fillers...but the "community" makes you keep your wallet and purses close.<//text>< pics>

<resp>None</resp><GmapID>0x80851426cf2065bb:0x5fd28f70e598cc93</GmapID></record></dataset><record>
<date>1577994691301< /date><text>There are several factors that are preventing this mall from being any better than what it is. The most significant is the ownership/management keeps changing which prevents the operation of this mall from realizing it's full potential to increase foot traffic and community space--it appears to be going in the right direction but could be doing a lot more. The idea of a centralized shopping mall was born out of a now archaic idea, hence, the failure of malls being stuck in the past and not forging into the future of adapting and innovating to meet the needs of the community and commercial trends. The 80s were years of capitalistic endeavors and excess--now, there is a bit of restraint and consciousness that curtails this to a certain extent. The "mall" concept cannot fight commercial trends nor change them enough to the point that it can drastically increase foot traffic and spending--there may be blips here and there but that brings to the second major factor that the mall can work towards is to increase its appeal to the community that supports the mall with more than just retail.

One of the unique appeals that demonstrates this, is the art gallery in the mall--I'm a huge fan of art, and by default since I consider myself an artist on several levels. This is an example of adapting, albeit there is no economic activity, it does support community and culture at least. If this were the 80s, it would be absurd to have an art gallery in the mall and I would laugh along with every 80s person at that time but now, it's making sense that community spaces should conglomerate into the mall, where storefronts give way to e-commerce and warehouses instead. Bringing in more service-based business also makes sense and of course you cannot go wrong with food/restaurant as well. The owner/operator of the mall should look into bringing in non-profit groups to increase foot traffic, offering workshops and seminars (in the empty spaces), maybe converting an empty space into a community rental space, for example. I was also a huge fan of the city operating services at the mall as well. I took advantage on several occasions before the advent of online services.

Also, the shrinking of luxury retailers in a shifting economy and demographics away from excess (and illogical) spending--should there really be that many jewelry stores in this mall? Prolly not. I did find it nifty that a college tried to have a branch in the mall but they must not have found it "profitable" enough. Perhaps that could be attempted again but with the community college or other public (cheaper) alternative.

Personally, I was never a fan the mall's approach some odd years ago to move all food kiosks/small restaurants into the food court area--the mall should dotted here and there to spread out the foot traffic. It looks like they are getting back into that layout.

I also have many gripes with the security (if that hasn't changed as well) and the limitations are too limiting. Private security makes sense on smaller scales--I think it makes sense of epic proportions to have city police officers permanently assigned to the mall, at least two. Presence alone does wonders! Not just the mall proper, but parking lots, connecting strip malls as well. Crime in the parking lots alone is enough to disrupt business and the impact on social/community cohesion is quite strong. Again, police presence really makes an impact. I love how the Vallejo PD are on bikes in downtown Vallejo during the farmer's markets. I would love seeing the same happen for the mall.

Collecting my thoughts and ideas back into focus--not all malls should be approached the same either, nor have the same intentions and goals in mind. There ought to be a sense of uniqueness and identity created. I don't expect franchises and retailers to setup shop here that are just a town away for more of the same, I expect more of a diverse "portfolio" of what the mall can offer. Local economy should be the key stone here. People should come together with the mall owner/management and lay out a plan for that.< /text><rate>4< /rate><Resp>None</Resp><gmapID>0x80851426cf2065bb:0x5fd28f70e598cc93<//gmapID><name>Aaron J Garcia<//name><user>106592008159121829310<//user>< pics>
None</pics>
</record></dataset><record>

< Text>
I'm not typically a mall person but this one's not that bad. There's a lot to do with your little kids, they have a jump/hop store that's $10 for all all day play which is awesome if you can bring someone to watch them play while you shop. They have a carousel that has two stories, playgrounds, Bungie jump, these weird huge animal things you ride and a train that goes around the mall. They also have a build a bear workshop, a Disney store, arcade, movie theater and candy stores so there's legit tons of stuff to do with the kiddos. For the teens and adults there's all the standard clothes stores, GameStop, and food. Not a bad place to blow a few hours< /Text>

<UserId.>108932492797021143142< /UserId.>< Rating>

< Review>
I used to love this mall, and some of the stores I still do. However, 2 things you should be aware of: #1 beware of closing time. If you get stuck on the wrong side or floor of the mall, you're going to be forced to go outside and take stairs to get back to your car. They don't care if you have little children or are 9 months pregnant & it is freezing outside. Especially beware of H & M, their employees are SO RUDE about closing time and they trap you on the top floor (with only an exit going outside) if you want to buy anything. 2nd, beware of the carousel at closing time. They have totally rude employees, two creepy males I am speaking of in particular, who close it down early (8:40 instead of 9). They don't care if you JUST bought a ticket (in front of him I might add, but he couldn't tell you they were closed) or that your 2 year old was so excited to ride. They are on their cell phones the whole time. One even started the ride before I had my child completely secure. Never going there again.< /Review>

< username>
Julian Cortez< /username>
< time>
1549337709832</time>
< rating>
3</rating>
< text>
Fifteen years ago this was a nice mall with a Chick- Fill-a but what I used to love the most, was the huge major department stores. I remember there was A two floor Mervyns with a full service hallmark card department and A Three floor Sears with huge appliance and electronic departments and I also remember Macy's had a full crystal ware department and JCPenney had photos with Santa during The Holidays. Fast forward fifteen years  both Mervyns and Sears left ,The Macy's and JCPenney stores here are not what they used to be and the entire mall is mash up of name brand and knock off stores and also a lot of overpriced "real gold and silver jewelry" kiosks. Though there are a few big name and quality stores like Dicks Sporting Goods and H&M not to mention there a lot of good athletic shoe stores here like Shoe Palace that are still worth coming here for anymore. I also want to add that this mall has a notorious reputation for being dangerous and unsafe due to the high number of crimes in and around the mall. I personally have fond memories here  but I rarely  come unless I need something last minute or I need to go to Dicks Sporting Goods but I still give it three stars, Just for the memories of the past.< /text>

<date>1531747751463< /date>< rate>
2</rate>
< review>
Maybe the rents to high, but they need to bring in more high end stores. The food court is ok. To many thrift shop type stores throughout the mall. Center isle of mall is  flooded with knockoff jewelers. 1 end of the mall has a playground which was ok, then they put in a huge carousel in the middle of the mall. Then they added electric animal riding scooters for kids and parents to ride around in. Now they have a train that cruises the mall walk ways. It's a disaster! Like what is going on here. All they are missing is a juggling act and animals doing tricks and it would be a full fledged circus. Bring in cabellas, bass pro shop, Louie Vitton, crate and barrel, ect... it's really sad seeing this mall head the direction it is. If you are looking for cheap, made in China, products solano mall has a bunch of stores that I'm sure you would love.</review>

< review>
It is not in a safe area of town. Many thefts happen daily in the stores people are never made aware of. Civilians themselves have been robbed, injured, had vehicles broken into or stolen, severely hurt and even killed. MANY large groups of teens and young adults linger here out of boredom and like to intimidate others.

As a woman, or a teenager, I wouldn't ever suggest going alone! There are very few stores that I would be hard pressed to need to go into for me to go to the mall. The only visits I make are to the movie theater which is on the outside of it and that is primarily it.

I find it sad considering this is pretty much all we have unless you travel out of town. It has been this way for several years now and not getting any better.< /review>
